nd their ideals of female autonomy. Flori will be read by those involved in the study of early modern literature and drama, women's studies, and the study of gender and sexuality in this period.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aCampiglia, Maddalena. 0aLiterature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  abilingual, italy, italian, literature, literary, pastoral, drama, europe, european, secularism, secular, women, female, gender, autonomy, sexuality, boscareccia, fable, torquato tasso, aminta, virgin, virginity, myth, diana, love, shepherd, marriage, relationship, lgbtqia, lgbtq, cult, death, grief, devotion, cultural studies, culture.1 aCox, Virginia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCox, Virginia.1 aKing, Margaret L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRabil, Albert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSampson, Lisa, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSampson, Lisa.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226092249423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226092249/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles